 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9m2vs","title":"parity: Graph constructor silently drops edges from dict-of-list adjacency input","description":"fnx.Graph({0: [1], 1: [0, 2], 2: [1]}) returns a graph with 3 nodes and 0 edges. nx.Graph(...) correctly parses it as adjacency-list, returning 3 nodes and 2 edges. _decode_dict_of_dicts_into handles dict-of-DICT shape but skips when the value is a list (continue at 'if not isinstance(nbrs, dict)'). Drop-in code that builds a graph from a dict-of-list adjacency representation gets a wrong graph silently. Same pre-existing pattern from br-r37-c1-lc3em (dict-of-dict input was originally handled, but list-of-neighbours was not). Fix: extend _decode_dict_of_dicts_into to also handle the dict-of-list case (and dict-of-set/tuple by iterating any iterable of neighbour nodes).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T08:48:21.921012966Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T08:53:41.082780910Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T08:53:41.080770904Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit ca5cc1f. Graph/DiGraph/MultiGraph/MultiDiGraph constructors now accept dict-of-list (and any iterable-valued dict) adjacency input matching nx.from_dict_of_lists. 11 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9mdsv","title":"parity: label_propagation_communities return type drift","description":"fnx.label_propagation_communities(G) returns dict_values([{0,1,2},...]) — a dict_values view object — while networkx returns a generator yielding sets. Drop-in code that does isinstance(result, types.GeneratorType) or relies on consuming once will diverge. Convert wrapper to yield sets directly (return iter(...)). File: python/franken_networkx/__init__.py (around line 17175).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-25T05:05:05.214287589Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T05:08:52.048798239Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T05:08:52.046958637Z","close_reason":"Invalid: NetworkX 3.6.1 and legacy oracle both return dict_values; existing wrapper and tests already match.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9yavb","title":"parity: utils.heaps {BinaryHeap, MinHeap, PairingHeap} + classes.function.frozen (4 surfaces)","description":"Two missing utility surfaces: networkx.utils.heaps exposes BinaryHeap, MinHeap, PairingHeap classes used as the default heap= kwarg in stoer_wagner and other algorithms; networkx.classes.function exposes frozen as a no-op exception-raising sentinel attached to frozen graphs by nx.freeze. franken_networkx surfaces neither. Add Python wrappers re-exporting these directly from nx (no graph-conversion needed; they are pure utilities).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-25T23:09:42.538123502Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T23:24:40.588218288Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T23:24:40.586349930Z","close_reason":"Shipped in 63cc1d9: BinaryHeap/MinHeap/PairingHeap re-exports + frozen sentinel. Verified BinaryHeap insert/min/pop, PairingHeap insert/min, frozen() raises NetworkXError as expected.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"br-r37-c1-aic4h","title":"Refactor 8 strategy_* coloring functions out of NX_DELEGATED","description":"Per coverage matrix invariant, public exports should be PY_WRAPPER not NX_DELEGATED — the convention is to keep nx imports inside private _xxx_via_nx helpers.

Refactor the 8 coloring strategy functions (strategy_largest_first, strategy_smallest_last, strategy_random_sequential, strategy_independent_set, strategy_connected_sequential, strategy_connected_sequential_bfs, strategy_connected_sequential_dfs, strategy_saturation_largest_first) to follow the convention.

Each currently has shape:
  def strategy_X(G, colors):
